<italic>Data Safety and Monitoring Board:</italic> Prof Andrew Farmer (chair), Professor of General Practice University of Oxford, United Kingdom; Dr Bruce Neal, University of Sydney, Australia; Prof Doris Young, University of Melbourne, Australia; Dr Say Beng Tan, Duke-NUS Medical School, Singapore <italic>The International Advisory Board</italic> will be chaired by Dr Sania Nishtar, President Heartfile (non-government organization), Pakistan.</p><sec id="FPar2"><title>Funding</title><p>The study is supported by a research award: Grant Ref No: MR/N006178/1 from the MRC/DFId/Wellcome Trust, UK. The funders had no role in the study design, data collection and analysis, decision to publish or preparation of the manuscript.</p></sec><sec id="FPar3"><title>Availability of data and materials</title><p>Not applicable.</p></sec><sec id="FPar4"><title>Authors&#x02019; contributions</title><p>THJ conceived the design of the trial, drafted the protocol and assembled the site teams and project management teams. AN, IJ and AdS with co-site PIs (JC, AH, AK) contributed to modifications and adaptions in the protocol as per local health systems in each country; MG and PA led the analytic plan, ELT also contributed to the analytic plan, EAF led the cost-effectiveness plan, MB contributed to the CEA plan and HLQ led the qualitative interviews planning. THJ assembled the TSC and DSMB with SE. THJ approved all components of the study and is the guarantor. All authors read and approved the final manuscript.</p></sec><sec id="FPar5"><title>Competing interests</title><p>The authors declare that they have no competing interests.</p></sec><sec id="FPar6"><title>Consent for publication</title><p>Not applicable.</p></sec><sec id="FPar7"><title>Ethics approval and consent to participate</title><p>Ethical approval has been obtained from the Ethics Review Committee at the Duke-NUS Graduate Medical School (Duke-NUS) in Singapore (NUS reference code: B-15-253), the International Centre for Diarrhoeal Disease Research, Bangladesh (ICDDR, B) in Dhaka, Bangladesh (ERC NO: PR-15104), the Aga Khan University (AKU) in Karachi, Pakistan (ERC Ref. No: 3833-CHS-ERC-15), the University of Kelaniya (UKe) in Colombo, Sri Lanka (ERC Ref. No: P/179/11/2015) and the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine (LSHTM) in the UK (LSHTM Ethics Ref: 10361).</p></sec><sec id="FPar8"><title>Informed consent</title><p>Written informed consent will be obtained prior to participant involvement in the study from: (1) hypertensive individuals in the pre- and post-intervention study, (2) stakeholders and 3) individuals who participate in interview sessions to investigate stakeholder experiences and attitudes towards the study intervention. The consent form is held by institutions (ICCDR, B, AKU and Uke) and is available for review by the Chief Investigator (THJ).</p></sec><sec id="FPar9"><title>Dissemination plan</title><p>
<italic>National Advisory Group:</italic> Each site is supported by the relevant provincial and national health officials, and members of professional organizations (cardiac and hypertension societies) and key stakeholders will serve on a &#x02018;national advisory group&#x02019;. This group has already been sensitized to the MCI strategies and their feedback incorporated into the trial. Regular meetings and dissemination of results are likely to enhance the scale-up of the trial.</p><p>
<italic>International Advisory Board:</italic> This board will include senior government representatives from WHO and Bangladesh, Pakistan and Sri Lanka, key health policy advocates and academic leadership.</p></sec><sec id="FPar10"><title>Trial governance and management</title><p>The trial is conducted per UK-MRC GCP framework with an independent Trial Steering Committee and Data Safety and Monitoring Board.</p></sec><sec id="FPar11"><title>Publisher&#x02019;s Note</title><p>Springer Nature remains neutral with regard to jurisdictional claims in published maps and institutional affiliations.</p></sec></ack><ref-list id="Bib1"><title>References</title><ref id="CR1"><label>1.</label><element-citation publication-type="journal"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Lopez</surname><given-names>AD</given-names></name><name><surname>Mathers</surname><given-names>CD</given-names></name><name><surname>Ezzati</surname><given-names>M</given-names></name><name><surname>Jamison</surname><given-names>DT</given-names></name><name><surname>Murray</surname><given-names>CJ</given-names></name></person-group><article-title>Global and regional burden of disease and risk factors, 2001: systematic analysis of population health data</article-title><source>Lancet</source><year>2006</year><volume>367</volume><fpage>1747</fpage><lpage>57</lpage><pub-id pub-id-type="doi">10.1016/S0140-6736(06)68770-9</pub-id><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">16731270</pub-id></element-citation></ref><ref id="CR2"><label>2.</label><element-citation publication-type="journal"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Lozano</surname><given-names>R</given-names></name><name><surname>Naghavi</surname><given-names>M</given-names></name><name><surname>Foreman</surname><given-names>K</given-names></name><name><surname>Lim</surname><given-names>S</given-names></name><name><surname>Shibuya</surname><given-names>K</given-names></name><name><surname>Aboyans</surname><given-names>V</given-names